This student will explore the atmospheric conditions that accompany dust devil formation by combining the vortex catalog with environmental measurements from the MEDA RDS dataset. For each detected vortex, they will extract variables such as air temperature, ground temperature, wind speed, wind direction, humidity, and pressure, then compare these conditions to periods when no vortices were observed. The goal is to determine whether dust devils preferentially occur under specific environmental conditions and to identify the factors that may promote vortex formation. This project introduces the student to planetary meteorology, environmental data analysis, and hypothesis testing while providing a pathway toward understanding the physical drivers of dust devil activity at Jezero Crater.

Big Question
"What atmospheric conditions favor dust devil formation?"
This uses your RDS data.

Week 1
Learn what the variables mean.
Introduce:
Pressure
Air temperature
Ground temperature
Wind speed
Wind direction
Relative humidity
Goal:
Understand the physical meaning of each measurement.

Week 2
Data exploration.
Create plots of:
Temperature versus time
Wind speed versus time
Humidity versus time
for several sols.
Questions:
What changes during the day?
Which variables are noisy?

Week 3
Match datasets.
For each vortex:
Extract:
Time
Sol
Ls
Then locate:
Temperature
Wind speed
Wind direction
Humidity
at the same time.
Build:
Master environmental table.
Example:
Sol
Ls
DeltaP
Temp
Wind
RH


Week 4
Look at vortex environments.
Questions:
When vortices occur:
Is temperature higher?
Is wind speed higher?
Is humidity lower?
Create simple boxplots.

Week 5
Create comparison samples.
Select:
200 vortex times
200 random non-vortex times
Compare variables.
This is where they begin doing actual science.

Week 6
Statistical testing.
Teach:
Means
Medians
Standard deviation
T-tests or nonparametric tests
Questions:
Are differences statistically significant?

Week 7
Interpretation.
Questions:
What conditions appear favorable?
Example findings:
Vortices occur during warmest part of day.
Vortices occur during periods of elevated turbulence.
Wind speed is modestly higher.

Week 8
Deliverable
A poster section titled:
Environmental Conditions Associated with Dust Devil Activity at Jezero Crater

